canonical:
  title: 入金謝差接伴表
  author: 金克己
  language: lzh
  text: 觀國之光遠賓王於漢闕遣臣以禮伻伴客於周原榮越分涯感塡胷次中謝 陪臣邈從靑徼將覲紫宸日月照臨雖藿向葵傾之有素山川悠遠恐萍漂蓬轉以無依何幸聖情尙憐羈迹差降皇皇之使導迎踽踽之行聯虎節之熒煌光生道路想龍顔之沕穆望極雲霄
  rtl: true
  vertical: true
lzh_formatted:
  title: 入金謝差接伴表
  author: 金克己
  language: lzh
  text: 觀國之光。遠賓王於漢闕。遣臣以禮。伻伴客於周原。榮越分涯。感塡胷次。中謝。 陪臣邈從靑徼。將覲紫宸。日月照臨。雖藿向葵傾之有素。山川悠遠。恐萍漂蓬轉以無依。何幸聖情。尙憐羈迹。差降皇皇之使。導迎踽踽之行。聯虎節之熒煌。光生道路。想龍顔之沕穆。望極雲霄。
korean:
  title: 금 나라에 들어가 영접사를 보내 주심을 사례하는 표
  author: 김극기
  language: kor
  text: |-
    상국에 과거를 보려고 멀리 궁궐에 조회하옵던 차에, 신하를 예(禮)로 보내 도중에 영접하오니, 영광이 분에 넘쳐 느낌이 가슴에 벅차도소이다. 중사(中謝)
    배신(陪臣)이 멀리 청구(靑邱)를 떠나 장차 자신(紫宸)께 뵈오려 함은 해와 달이 조림(照臨)함에 비록 평소로부터 해바라기가 해를 보고 기울어지듯 하오나, 산천(山川)이 멀고 멀어 부평초(浮萍草)가 떠돌 듯, 의지할 바 없음을 두려워해서였는데 어쩌면 다행히 성상께서 나그네의 신세를 어여삐 여기사 사자를 내려보내시어 이 외로운 일행을 맞아 주시오니, 호절(虎節)이 찬란히 늘어섬에 도로에 생색(生色)이 오며, 거룩한 용안(龍顔)을 상상하면서 운소(雲霄)를 그지없이 바라옵나이다.
  url: https://db.itkc.or.kr/dir/item?itemId=BT#dir/node?dataId=ITKC_BT_1365A_0380_010_0260&viewSync=OT
  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Memorial Expressing Gratitude for the Dispatch of an Envoy to Receive Us Upon Entering the Jin Realm
  author: Kim Geuk-gi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I gaze upon the glory of the realm,
    Where distant envoys bow at the imperial gates.
    Yet courteous officials are sent forth,
    To welcome this humble delegation on the road.

    Such honor exceeds all measure—
    My heart swells with overwhelming gratitude.

    [In the middle of my thanks]

    I, a lowly attendant, have journeyed far from the blue mountains,
    Hoping one day to glimpse the purple palace.
    The sun and moon look down upon all below,
    And as the sunflower has always bent toward the light,
    So too my heart turns naturally toward your grace.

    Yet the mountains and rivers stretch endlessly before me,
    And I drift like floating duckweed upon uncertain waters,
    Finding no sure harbor for my weary soul.

    What fortune beyond measure—
    That Your Majesty's compassion falls even upon a wanderer like myself!
    You have sent your messengers in splendor,
    To greet this solitary procession on the dusty road.
    The tiger-emblazoned insignia gleams brilliantly,
    Casting light across our humble path.

    And when I imagine the resplendent countenance of the Dragon Throne,
    I gaze upward through the clouds and sky,
    Reaching ever toward that distant majesty.
  footnotes:
    - The 'blue mountains' (青邱) refer to Korea, the author's homeland.
    - The 'purple palace' (紫宸) is a traditional poetic reference to the imperial court.
    - The sunflower metaphor suggests the natural inclination of subjects to revere their sovereign.
    - The floating duckweed represents the author's anxiety about traveling far from home without assured support.
    - The tiger-emblazoned insignia (虎節) symbolizes the official authority and dignity of the imperial messenger.
